# linux_abi/u_caps.ad -- the Linux POSIX capabilities family (capget/capset).
#
# Real Debian userland reaches for the POSIX.1e capability API constantly:
#
#   * capget(header, data)   nr 125  -> read a task's effective/permitted/
#                                       inheritable cap sets (or version-probe)
#   * capset(header, data)   nr 126  -> set the calling task's cap sets
#
# libcap (`capsh --print`, `getcap`/`setcap`'s runtime checks), systemd's
# CapabilityBoundingSet plumbing, ping's cap_net_raw drop-after-bind, dpkg/apt
# privilege checks — they all round-trip these two syscalls. Until now both
# fell through to the ENOSYS default, so any such tool saw a bogus failure.
#
# ARCHITECTURE NOTE -- caps are a LINUX-ABI concept that ALSO gates a small,
# explicit set of kernel operations whose admin authority is naturally
# expressed in POSIX-cap terms. Hamnix's native security model remains Plan 9
# per-process namespaces + file-server boundary enforcement; caps SUPPLEMENT
# (do not replace) the hostowner-uid gate on operations that real Linux
# tooling already drops/raises caps around.
#
# Audit-driven (docs/audit_gap_vs_linux_2026-06-13.md): the operations gated
# on the calling task's effective cap set are now REAL, not paper. As of
# F10-7-cap-wiring:
#
#   * CAP_SYS_ADMIN (bit 21)  -> mount(2) (nr 165) in u_syscalls.ad's
#                                 _u_mount handler. Linux's MS_BIND family
#                                 always requires CAP_SYS_ADMIN; we honour
#                                 the same constraint for the fuse-mount
#                                 path.
#   * CAP_NET_ADMIN (bit 12)  -> host-level admin writes inside the `#I`
#                                 IP server: /net/ipifc/ctl, /net/addr,
#                                 /net/dns (server pin). Gated inside
#                                 drivers/net/devnet.ad's devnet_perm_check.
#                                 hostowner uid (1) is still required; lack
#                                 of CAP_NET_ADMIN in the caller's effective
#                                 set additionally denies the op (EPERM).
#
# Other cap bits remain modelled-but-not-gated; capget/capset round-trip
# fidelity for libcap (capsh / ping / systemd) is preserved either way.
# Unseen tasks lazily default to the FULL cap set (ucaps_ensure_seeded), so
# native code paths and as-yet-unconverted Linux paths see no behaviour
# change unless the task explicitly capset()s caps away.
#
# Layer note: a confined Layer-2 leaf. It calls only current_idx_get() (the
# task-slot key) + the user-pointer-safe copy helpers (copy_from_user /
# copy_to_user). It never touches 9P / Chan / Layer-1 code. u_syscalls.ad
# imports US (the dispatch arms forward here), the same shape as u_pidfd.ad.

from kernel.sched.core import (
    current_idx_get,
    NTASKS,
)
from mm.uaccess import (
    copy_from_user, copy_to_user,
)
from kernel.printk.printk import (
    printk0, printk1,
)


# =====================================================================
# Linux capability ABI constants
# =====================================================================
#
# struct __user_cap_header_struct { __u32 version; int pid; }   (8 bytes)
# struct __user_cap_data_struct   { __u32 effective;
#                                    __u32 permitted;
#                                    __u32 inheritable; }        (12 bytes each)
#
# _LINUX_CAPABILITY_VERSION_3 is the current preferred version; libcap probes
# for it by calling capget with data==NULL and reading the version the kernel
# writes back. v1 carries ONE __user_cap_data_struct (caps 0..31); v2/v3 carry
# TWO (element [0] = caps 0..31, element [1] = caps 32..63).
CAP_VERSION_1: uint32 = 0x19980330
CAP_VERSION_2: uint32 = 0x20071026
CAP_VERSION_3: uint32 = 0x20080522

CAP_HEADER_SZ: uint64 = 8           # { __u32 version; int pid; }
CAP_DATA_SZ:   uint64 = 12          # { __u32 eff; __u32 perm; __u32 inher; }

# Linux negative-errno convention (subset we return).
CAPS_EPERM:   int64 = -1
CAPS_EFAULT:  int64 = -14
CAPS_EINVAL:  int64 = -22


# =====================================================================
# per-task capability store
# =====================================================================
#
# Three 64-bit cap sets per task (effective / permitted / inheritable), keyed
# by task slot exactly the way the rlimit store (kernel/sched/core.ad
# g_rlim_cur/g_rlim_max) is keyed. The per-task tables are sized to the
# scheduler's NTASKS (imported above) and the bounds checks read that imported
# NTASKS DIRECTLY, so a future lift updates the cap store atomically. The bound
# historically lagged at 16 (a local UCAPS_NTASKS literal) while core.ad moved
# to 64: a task in slots 16-63 hit the out-of-range guard, so ucaps_set silently
# dropped its (often restricted) cap write while the getters returned 0 — i.e.
# its intended cap policy was never stored. Sizing to NTASKS keeps every live
# slot in range. A parallel "seeded" bitmap lazily defaults a never-before-seen
# task to the full (root-like) cap set on first access. The Array dims below
# stay literal (Adder requires literal sizes) but are == NTASKS. (Adder forbids
# initialising a global from another global, so there is no local alias to drift.)
ucaps_effective:   Array[256, uint64]
ucaps_permitted:   Array[256, uint64]
ucaps_inheritable: Array[256, uint64]
ucaps_seeded:      Array[256, uint8]      # 0 = never touched, 1 = initialised

# The full 64-bit cap set (all of caps 0..63 set). Real Linux caps top out
# around bit 40, but modelling all 64 bits is harmless and keeps the mask
# arithmetic simple.
UCAPS_FULL: uint64 = 0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFF


def ucaps_init():
    # Boot-time reset: every slot un-seeded, all sets cleared. Slots default
    # lazily to full caps on first touch (ucaps_ensure_seeded).
    i: uint64 = 0
    while i < NTASKS:
        ucaps_effective[i]   = 0
        ucaps_permitted[i]   = 0
        ucaps_inheritable[i] = 0
        ucaps_seeded[i]      = 0
        i = i + 1


def ucaps_ensure_seeded(slot: uint64):
    # Lazily default an unseen task to the full (root-like) cap set the first
    # time it is observed. Mirrors the "init/root context gets the full set"
    # common case; a child that forks from such a context re-defaults to full
    # here, which is the correct root-like answer for the Debian tools that
    # consult caps. Out-of-range slots are ignored.
    if slot >= NTASKS:
        return
    if ucaps_seeded[slot] != 0:
        return
    ucaps_effective[slot]   = UCAPS_FULL
    ucaps_permitted[slot]   = UCAPS_FULL
    ucaps_inheritable[slot] = 0          # Linux default: empty inheritable set
    ucaps_seeded[slot]      = 1


def ucaps_get_effective(slot: uint64) -> uint64:
    if slot >= NTASKS:
        return 0
    ucaps_ensure_seeded(slot)
    return ucaps_effective[slot]


def ucaps_get_permitted(slot: uint64) -> uint64:
    if slot >= NTASKS:
        return 0
    ucaps_ensure_seeded(slot)
    return ucaps_permitted[slot]


def ucaps_get_inheritable(slot: uint64) -> uint64:
    if slot >= NTASKS:
        return 0
    ucaps_ensure_seeded(slot)
    return ucaps_inheritable[slot]


def ucaps_set(slot: uint64, eff: uint64, perm: uint64, inher: uint64):
    if slot >= NTASKS:
        return
    ucaps_effective[slot]   = eff
    ucaps_permitted[slot]   = perm
    ucaps_inheritable[slot] = inher
    ucaps_seeded[slot]      = 1


# =====================================================================
# header version validation
# =====================================================================
#
# Returns 1 for a version we honour (v1/v2/v3), 0 otherwise.
def _ucaps_version_ok(ver: uint32) -> int32:
    if ver == CAP_VERSION_1:
        return 1
    if ver == CAP_VERSION_2:
        return 1
    if ver == CAP_VERSION_3:
        return 1
    return 0


# How many __user_cap_data_struct elements a header version carries: 1 for v1,
# 2 for v2/v3.
def _ucaps_ndata(ver: uint32) -> uint64:
    if ver == CAP_VERSION_1:
        return 1
    return 2


# =====================================================================
# capget(header, data)  --  nr 125
# =====================================================================
#
# int capget(cap_user_header_t header, cap_user_data_t data)
#   a0 = header pointer, a1 = data pointer.
#
#   * header == NULL              -> EFAULT (the header is always required).
#   * data == NULL                -> the version-PROBE form: write the kernel's
#                                    preferred version (v3) back into
#                                    header.version and return 0. This is how
#                                    libcap negotiates the ABI.
#   * unrecognised header.version -> rewrite header.version to the preferred
#                                    version and return EINVAL (matches Linux).
#   * otherwise                   -> copy the target task's three cap sets out
#                                    into the data array (two 32-bit halves per
#                                    64-bit set: [0]=low 32, [1]=high 32).
#
# pid==0 (or the caller's own slot) targets the current task. We only model the
# current-task case for the data read; a non-self pid is accepted but reports
# the current task's caps (sufficient for the libcap round-trip — capsh/ping
# query self). Out-of-our-knowledge tasks lazily default to full caps.
def ucaps_capget(a0: uint64, a1: uint64) -> int64:
    if a0 == 0:
        return CAPS_EFAULT
    # Read the 8-byte header { __u32 version; int pid; }.
    hdr: Array[8, uint8]
    if copy_from_user(cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), a0, CAP_HEADER_SZ) != 0:
        return CAPS_EFAULT
    ver: uint32 = cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]))[0]

    # Version-probe / bad-version handling: if the version is not one we
    # honour, rewrite the header to our preferred version. For the NULL-data
    # probe form this is the negotiation path and returns 0; for a bad version
    # with non-NULL data Linux returns EINVAL after the rewrite.
    if _ucaps_version_ok(ver) == 0:
        cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]))[0] = CAP_VERSION_3
        if copy_to_user(a0, cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), CAP_HEADER_SZ) != 0:
            return CAPS_EFAULT
        if a1 == 0:
            return 0
        return CAPS_EINVAL

    # data == NULL: pure version probe. Echo the (valid) version back so libcap
    # sees a stable, accepted version and return 0.
    if a1 == 0:
        cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]))[0] = ver
        if copy_to_user(a0, cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), CAP_HEADER_SZ) != 0:
            return CAPS_EFAULT
        return 0

    # Resolve the target slot. The header pid field (offset 4) selects the
    # task; 0 means the current task. We model self (current) caps.
    slot: uint64 = current_idx_get()

    eff:   uint64 = ucaps_get_effective(slot)
    perm:  uint64 = ucaps_get_permitted(slot)
    inher: uint64 = ucaps_get_inheritable(slot)

    ndata: uint64 = _ucaps_ndata(ver)

    # Assemble the data array in a kernel buffer, then copy it out in one shot.
    # Each __user_cap_data_struct is { eff_lo, perm_lo, inher_lo } for element
    # [0] and { eff_hi, perm_hi, inher_hi } for element [1].
    out: Array[24, uint8]        # max 2 * 12 bytes
    o: Ptr[uint32] = cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&out[0]))
    # element [0] -- caps 0..31 (low 32 bits)
    o[0] = cast[uint32](eff   & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    o[1] = cast[uint32](perm  & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    o[2] = cast[uint32](inher & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    if ndata == 2:
        # element [1] -- caps 32..63 (high 32 bits)
        o[3] = cast[uint32]((eff   >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFF)
        o[4] = cast[uint32]((perm  >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFF)
        o[5] = cast[uint32]((inher >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFF)

    if copy_to_user(a1, cast[uint64](&out[0]), ndata * CAP_DATA_SZ) != 0:
        return CAPS_EFAULT
    return 0


# =====================================================================
# capset(header, data)  --  nr 126
# =====================================================================
#
# int capset(cap_user_header_t header, cap_user_data_t data)
#   a0 = header pointer, a1 = data pointer.
#
#   * header == NULL / data == NULL -> EFAULT (both required for a set).
#   * unrecognised header.version   -> rewrite header to preferred + EINVAL.
#   * header.pid must be 0 or the caller's own tid; Linux forbids setting
#     another process's caps via this syscall -> EPERM otherwise.
#   * standard rule enforcement (common case, no CAP_SETPCAP modelled):
#       - new permitted MUST be a subset of old permitted (a process can only
#         DROP permitted caps; adding a bit not already permitted -> EPERM).
#       - new effective MUST be a subset of new permitted (-EPERM otherwise).
#       - inheritable is modelled leniently (any value accepted).
def ucaps_capset(a0: uint64, a1: uint64) -> int64:
    if a0 == 0 or a1 == 0:
        return CAPS_EFAULT
    # Read the 8-byte header.
    hdr: Array[8, uint8]
    if copy_from_user(cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), a0, CAP_HEADER_SZ) != 0:
        return CAPS_EFAULT
    ver: uint32 = cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]))[0]
    pid: int32  = cast[Ptr[int32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]) + 4)[0]

    if _ucaps_version_ok(ver) == 0:
        cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]))[0] = CAP_VERSION_3
        if copy_to_user(a0, cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), CAP_HEADER_SZ) != 0:
            return CAPS_EFAULT
        return CAPS_EINVAL

    slot: uint64 = current_idx_get()

    # capset may only target the calling thread: pid 0 or the caller's own tid.
    # current_idx_get is the slot, not the Linux tid, but pid 0 is the
    # overwhelmingly common libcap call; a non-zero pid that does not match the
    # caller is rejected with EPERM. We treat pid==(our own pid) as allowed by
    # forwarding through; the conservative model rejects any other non-zero pid.
    if pid != 0:
        # Reject setting another process's caps. (We cannot cheaply map slot ->
        # Linux tid here without a core import, so the strict-but-safe rule is:
        # only pid==0 is the self form. A real tid-match would also be allowed
        # but libcap always passes 0 for self.)
        return CAPS_EPERM

    ndata: uint64 = _ucaps_ndata(ver)

    # Read the data array { eff, perm, inher } * ndata.
    inb: Array[24, uint8]
    if copy_from_user(cast[uint64](&inb[0]), a1, ndata * CAP_DATA_SZ) != 0:
        return CAPS_EFAULT
    di: Ptr[uint32] = cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&inb[0]))

    new_eff:   uint64 = cast[uint64](di[0])
    new_perm:  uint64 = cast[uint64](di[1])
    new_inher: uint64 = cast[uint64](di[2])
    if ndata == 2:
        new_eff   = new_eff   | (cast[uint64](di[3]) << 32)
        new_perm  = new_perm  | (cast[uint64](di[4]) << 32)
        new_inher = new_inher | (cast[uint64](di[5]) << 32)

    # Rule enforcement against the task's CURRENT (old) sets.
    old_perm: uint64 = ucaps_get_permitted(slot)

    # new permitted must be a subset of old permitted: every bit set in
    # new_perm must already be set in old_perm. Equivalent: (new & ~old) == 0.
    if (new_perm & ~old_perm) != 0:
        return CAPS_EPERM

    # new effective must be a subset of new permitted.
    if (new_eff & ~new_perm) != 0:
        return CAPS_EPERM

    # inheritable: lenient (accept as given).
    ucaps_set(slot, new_eff, new_perm, new_inher)
    return 0


# =====================================================================
# Boot self-test  --  [CAPS] PASS / FAIL  (boot:37.caps)
# =====================================================================
#
# Exercises capget/capset directly against the real per-task cap store, driving
# the SAME handler entry points the nr 125/126 dispatch arms call. Boot-context
# pointers are kernel-mapped and resolve through copy_from_user/copy_to_user
# the same way rlimit_selftest's stack buffers do, so no userland binary is
# needed. Steps (mirroring the required C-fixture assertions):
#
#   (1) version-probe capget (data == NULL)  -> header.version becomes v3, rc 0
#   (2) capget(self) reports the seeded full effective/permitted sets
#   (3) capset(self) DROPPING one permitted cap, then capget asserts the drop
#   (4) capset(self) trying to ADD a permitted bit back -> EPERM
#
# caps_selftest is the entry init/main.ad's boot:37.caps gate calls. It returns
# 1 on success, 0 on any failure (matching rlimit_selftest's convention).

# A single Linux capability bit we drop/re-add in the test. CAP_NET_RAW is 13 --
# the cap `ping` keeps to open raw sockets, a natural real-world example.
CAP_NET_RAW_BIT: uint64 = 13

# --- Cap bits that actually gate kernel operations -------------------
# These two are the audit-wired bits (see file header). Real Linux
# <linux/capability.h> values; full-cap-set defaulted, so legacy code
# paths pass automatically until a task explicitly drops the bit via
# capset(2).
CAP_NET_ADMIN_BIT: uint64 = 12      # ipifc/ctl, dns server pin, addr
CAP_SYS_ADMIN_BIT: uint64 = 21      # mount(2) (fuse type)


def ucaps_self_has(cap_bit: uint64) -> int32:
    # 1 iff the calling task's EFFECTIVE cap set has `cap_bit` set; 0
    # otherwise. Drives the two real gates listed in the file header.
    # An unseen task lazily defaults to the full set, so this returns 1
    # for any task that has not explicitly capset()'d the bit away.
    slot: uint64 = current_idx_get()
    eff: uint64 = ucaps_get_effective(slot)
    mask: uint64 = cast[uint64](1) << cap_bit
    if (eff & mask) != 0:
        return 1
    return 0


def caps_selftest() -> int32:
    ucaps_init()
    slot: uint64 = current_idx_get()

    # --- (1) version-probe capget (data == NULL) ---------------------
    hdr: Array[8, uint8]
    # Plant a deliberately bogus version so the probe path must rewrite it.
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]))[0] = 0xDEADBEEF
    cast[Ptr[int32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]) + 4)[0] = 0
    rc: int64 = ucaps_capget(cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), 0)
    if rc != 0:
        printk1("[CAPS] FAIL version-probe rc=%d\n", cast[uint64](rc))
        return 0
    probed_ver: uint32 = cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]))[0]
    if probed_ver != CAP_VERSION_3:
        printk1("[CAPS] FAIL probe ver=%x != 0x20080522\n",
                cast[uint64](probed_ver))
        return 0

    # --- (2) capget(self): seeded full effective/permitted -----------
    # Use a valid v3 header now.
    cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]))[0] = CAP_VERSION_3
    cast[Ptr[int32]](cast[uint64](&hdr[0]) + 4)[0] = 0
    data: Array[24, uint8]
    rc = ucaps_capget(cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), cast[uint64](&data[0]))
    if rc != 0:
        printk1("[CAPS] FAIL capget(self) rc=%d\n", cast[uint64](rc))
        return 0
    dp: Ptr[uint32] = cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&data[0]))
    eff0: uint64  = cast[uint64](dp[0]) | (cast[uint64](dp[3]) << 32)
    perm0: uint64 = cast[uint64](dp[1]) | (cast[uint64](dp[4]) << 32)
    if eff0 != UCAPS_FULL or perm0 != UCAPS_FULL:
        printk1("[CAPS] FAIL default not full eff=%x\n", eff0)
        printk1("[CAPS]      perm=%x\n", perm0)
        return 0
    printk0("[CAPS] PASS default cap set is full (root-like)\n")

    # --- (3) capset(self) dropping CAP_NET_RAW from permitted+effective
    drop_mask: uint64 = ~(cast[uint64](1) << CAP_NET_RAW_BIT)
    new_perm: uint64 = UCAPS_FULL & drop_mask
    new_eff:  uint64 = UCAPS_FULL & drop_mask
    # Build the v3 data array (2 elements) to set.
    setd: Array[24, uint8]
    sp: Ptr[uint32] = cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&setd[0]))
    sp[0] = cast[uint32](new_eff   & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    sp[1] = cast[uint32](new_perm  & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    sp[2] = 0                                          # inheritable lo
    sp[3] = cast[uint32]((new_eff  >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    sp[4] = cast[uint32]((new_perm >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    sp[5] = 0                                          # inheritable hi
    rc = ucaps_capset(cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), cast[uint64](&setd[0]))
    if rc != 0:
        printk1("[CAPS] FAIL capset drop rc=%d\n", cast[uint64](rc))
        return 0
    # capget again and assert CAP_NET_RAW is gone from permitted+effective.
    rc = ucaps_capget(cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), cast[uint64](&data[0]))
    if rc != 0:
        printk1("[CAPS] FAIL capget-after-drop rc=%d\n", cast[uint64](rc))
        return 0
    eff1: uint64  = cast[uint64](dp[0]) | (cast[uint64](dp[3]) << 32)
    perm1: uint64 = cast[uint64](dp[1]) | (cast[uint64](dp[4]) << 32)
    net_raw_bit: uint64 = cast[uint64](1) << CAP_NET_RAW_BIT
    if (perm1 & net_raw_bit) != 0:
        printk0("[CAPS] FAIL CAP_NET_RAW still in permitted after drop\n")
        return 0
    if (eff1 & net_raw_bit) != 0:
        printk0("[CAPS] FAIL CAP_NET_RAW still in effective after drop\n")
        return 0
    printk0("[CAPS] PASS dropped CAP_NET_RAW persisted in the store\n")

    # --- (4) capset trying to ADD a permitted bit back -> EPERM ------
    # Now permitted lacks CAP_NET_RAW; ask to set it back -> must be EPERM
    # (cannot raise permitted above the current set).
    addd: Array[24, uint8]
    ap: Ptr[uint32] = cast[Ptr[uint32]](cast[uint64](&addd[0]))
    ap[0] = cast[uint32](UCAPS_FULL & 0xFFFFFFFF)      # eff lo (full again)
    ap[1] = cast[uint32](UCAPS_FULL & 0xFFFFFFFF)      # perm lo (full again)
    ap[2] = 0
    ap[3] = cast[uint32]((UCAPS_FULL >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    ap[4] = cast[uint32]((UCAPS_FULL >> 32) & 0xFFFFFFFF)
    ap[5] = 0
    rc = ucaps_capset(cast[uint64](&hdr[0]), cast[uint64](&addd[0]))
    if rc != CAPS_EPERM:
        printk1("[CAPS] FAIL add-cap rc=%d (expected EPERM -1)\n",
                cast[uint64](rc))
        return 0
    printk0("[CAPS] PASS adding a permitted bit rejected with EPERM\n")

    # --- (5) gate semantics: ucaps_self_has reflects the current store
    # Audit-wired gates: CAP_NET_ADMIN gates /net/ipifc/ctl (devnet
    # perm-check), CAP_SYS_ADMIN gates mount(2) (linux_abi _u_mount).
    # Both reach the in-kernel store through ucaps_self_has() — verify
    # that DROPpping each bit flips ucaps_self_has from 1 to 0 and that
    # restoring the seeded full set flips it back. This is the real
    # proof the cap-set drives the gate decision (not paper).
    # Drop CAP_NET_ADMIN + CAP_SYS_ADMIN from effective.
    na_bit: uint64 = cast[uint64](1) << CAP_NET_ADMIN_BIT
    sa_bit: uint64 = cast[uint64](1) << CAP_SYS_ADMIN_BIT
    cur_eff: uint64 = ucaps_get_effective(slot)
    cur_perm: uint64 = ucaps_get_permitted(slot)
    cur_inh: uint64 = ucaps_get_inheritable(slot)
    ucaps_set(slot, cur_eff & ~(na_bit | sa_bit), cur_perm, cur_inh)
    if ucaps_self_has(CAP_NET_ADMIN_BIT) != 0:
        printk0("[CAPS] FAIL CAP_NET_ADMIN still effective after drop\n")
        return 0
    if ucaps_self_has(CAP_SYS_ADMIN_BIT) != 0:
        printk0("[CAPS] FAIL CAP_SYS_ADMIN still effective after drop\n")
        return 0
    printk0("[CAPS] PASS gate sees CAP_NET_ADMIN dropped\n")
    printk0("[CAPS] PASS gate sees CAP_SYS_ADMIN dropped\n")

    # Re-seed the slot so the boot task is left in a clean (full-cap) state.
    ucaps_seeded[slot] = 0
    ucaps_ensure_seeded(slot)
    if ucaps_self_has(CAP_NET_ADMIN_BIT) == 0:
        printk0("[CAPS] FAIL CAP_NET_ADMIN missing after restore\n")
        return 0
    if ucaps_self_has(CAP_SYS_ADMIN_BIT) == 0:
        printk0("[CAPS] FAIL CAP_SYS_ADMIN missing after restore\n")
        return 0
    printk0("[CAPS] PASS gate restored CAP_NET_ADMIN + CAP_SYS_ADMIN\n")

    printk0("[CAPS] PASS\n")
    return 1
